The dataset includes information about student achievement in secondary education of two Potugese schools. It has 382 observations and 35 variables. The variables are student grades, and demographic, social and school related features.

The dataset is a combination of two datasets: Mathematics (mat) and Portugese language (por).

3 Personal hypothesis

I chose the following four variables to study their relationships with high/low alcohol consumption:

sex - students sex (binary: F - female or M - male) Males are more likely to have high alcohol consumption.

Pstatus - parents cohabitation status (binary: T - living together or A - apart) Students with parents living apart are more likely to have high alcohol consumption.

studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours) Students with less study time are more likely to have high alcohol consumption.

absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93) Students with high number of school absences are more likely to have high alcohol consumption.

There seems to be evidence for 1), 3) and 4), but not for 2).

6 Explore the predictive power of the model

Fit the same model, but drop the non significant variable Pstatus.

m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + studytime + absences, data, family = "binomial")

probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

data <- mutate(data, probability = probabilities)
data <- mutate(data, prediction = probability > 0.5)

table(high_use = data$high_use, prediction = data$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   10
##    TRUE     88   26

The model correcly predicted 258 to be FALSE when they actually were FALSE, and 26 to be TRUE when they actually were TRUE. The model incorrectly predicted 10 to be TRUE when they actually were FALSE, and 88 to be FALSE when they actually were TRUE.

g <- ggplot(data, aes(x = high_use, y = probability))
g+geom_point()

The model predicts most of the FALSE values correctly, but fails to predict a large proportion of the TRUE values.

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = data$high_use, prob = data$probability)
## [1] 0.2565445

26 percent were predicted incorrectly. This could also be read from the previous table (88+10)/(258+10+88+26).

loss_func(class = data$high_use, prob = 0)
## [1] 0.2984293

Define the probability of high_use as zero for each individual. 30 percent were predicted incorrectly. The model preforms better (but not much better!) than simply giving all probability 0.

The Boston data set includes information about Housing Values in Suburbs of Boston. It has 506 observations and 14 variables. The Boston data set contains the following variables:

crim: per capita crime rate by town.

zn: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.

indus: proportion of non-retail business acres per town.

chas: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).

nox: nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).

rm: average number of rooms per dwelling.

age: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.

dis: weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.

rad: index of accessibility to radial highways.

tax: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.

ptratio: pupil-teacher ratio by town.

black: 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.

lstat: lower status of the population (percent).

medv: median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
 y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads),   cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}


plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Chapter 5: Dimensionality reduction techniques

In this chapter, we learn the basics of two data science based ways of reducing the dimensions. The key method is principal component analysis (PCA), which reduces any number of measured (continuous) and correlated variables into a few uncorrelated components that collect together as much variance as possible from the original variables. Multiple correspondence analysis (MCA) and other variations of CA bring us similar possibilities in the world of discrete variables, even nominal scale (classified) variables, by finding a suitable transformation into continuous scales and then reducing the dimensions quite analogously with the PCA.

# Load the data

Expected years of education is the variable that is closest to normally distributed, as most countries are located around the mean value of 13.18 years. Life expectancy at birth is clearly skewed to the right with most countries taking values around 75 years. On the other hand, Gross national income, Maternal mortality ratio and Adolescent birth rate are skewed to the left, with most countries taking low values on these variables. Gross national income has however the largest variation, as it takes values from 581 to 123124.

The strongest positive correlation is found between Life expectany at birth and Expected years of education (0.789) and between Adolescent birth rate and Maternal mortality ratio (0.759). Countries with high life expectancy at birth also tend to have high expected years of education. The strongest negative correlation is found between Maternal mortality ratio and Life expectancy at birth (-0.857). The weakest correlation is found between Gross national income and the ratio of labour force participation of females and males (-0.022).

In the non standardized data, Gross National Income has much larger variance than the rest of the variables. PCA assumes that variables with larger variance are more important than variables with smaller variance. Therefore, the long arrow of Gross National Income dominates the figure, and the rest of the arrows are of length zero. PC1 simply captures the variability of the variable with largest variance, Gross National Income, and countries with low values on this variable are to the right side of the plot (most countries) and countries with high values are to the left side of the plot.

3 Principal component analysis (PCA), standardized data

# standardize the variables
human_std <- scale(human)

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method)
pca_human_std <- prcomp(human_std)
s_std <- summary(pca_human_std)

# the percentages of variance 
pca_pr_std <- round(100*s_std$importance[2, ], digits = 1)
pca_pr_std
##  PC1  PC2  PC3  PC4  PC5  PC6  PC7  PC8 
## 53.6 16.2  9.6  7.6  5.5  3.6  2.6  1.3

Now PC1 captures 53.6 percent of the variability in the data and PC2 16.2 percent. Using these two components, we fail to explain ~30 percent of the variability in the data.

# create object pc_lab to be used as axis labels
pc_lab_std <- paste0(names(pca_pr_std), " (", pca_pr_std, "%)")

# draw a biplot
biplot(pca_human_std, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = pc_lab_std[1], ylab = pc_lab_std[2])

The data set is now standardized, meaning that the variance is 1 for all variables. All arrows are therefore of similar length, and none of them dominate the figure like in the non standardized case.

The small angle between Maternal mortality ratio and Adolescent birth rate shows the strong positive correlation between them. Expected years of education, Life expectancy at birth and Gross National Income are positivley correlated with each other, but negatively correlated with Maternal mortality ratio and Adolescent birth rate (due to the wide angle between them). Percent Representation in Parliament and the ratio of labour force participation of females and males are positivley correlated with each other, but these are not correlated with the feature that PC1 represents (due to orthogonality between them).

4 Personal interpretations

PC1 captures the overall health and development in a country. To the left is healthy countries with high life expectancy and low maternal mortality and to he right is unhealthy countries with high frequency of teenage births and low expected years of education.

PC2 captures the degree of gender equality in a country, where gender equality is measured by the ratio of labour force participation of females and males and by Percent Representation in Parliament.

As we can see from the figure, Nordic and Western European countries are in the left top of the figure and ranks high in both health and equality. Oppositely, in the rigth bottom with bad health and low gender equality is for example Niger.

Chapter 6: Analysis of longitudinal data

Analysing the RATS data set

A nutrition study conducted in three groups of rats (Crowder and Hand, 1990). The three groups were put on different diets, and each animals body weight (grams) was recorded repeatedly (approximately weekly, except in week seven when two recordings were taken) over a 9-week period. The question of most interest is whether the growth profiles of the three groups differ. https://mooc.helsinki.fi/pluginfile.php/78192/course/section/3817/MABS4IODS.pdf

In more detail, we want to study the diffecences between the variable of interest, that is the weight of the individual rats, and the groups as well as the change of the weight in time.

Next, take a look at the data. We plot the weakly measurement points for each rat distinguished by diet group.

Weight seems to be increasing in all diet groups, but we are interested wether one diet seems to be more efficient than the other one.

Before further analyses, we plot the standardised Weight. We do this to get rid of the fact that rats who have higher weight at the beginning tend to have higher weight throughout the study.

# Standardise the variable Weight
RATSL <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Time) %>%
  mutate(stdweight = (Weight - mean(Weight))/sd(Weight) ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Plot again with the standardised Weight
ggplot(RATSL, aes(x = Time, y = stdweight, linetype = ID)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = rep(1:10, times=4)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ Group, labeller = label_both) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "standardized weight")

Next, we produce graphs showing average (mean) profiles for each diet group along with some indication of the variation of the observations at each time point.

# Create the summary data RATSS with the mean and standard error of the variable Weight
# Number of Time, baseline (Time 1) included
n <- RATSL$Time %>% unique() %>% length()

# Summary data with mean and standard error of Weight by Group and Time
RATSS <- RATSL %>%
  group_by(Group, Time) %>%
  summarise( mean = mean(Weight), se = (sd(Weight)/sqrt(n)) ) %>%
  ungroup()


# Plot the mean profiles

  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight) +/- se(Weight)")

The confidence intervals for the profiles for each treatment group do not overlap, which indicate that there is difference between the groups.

Before modeling the data, we need to check for and remove outliers.

# Create a summary data by Group and ID with mean as the summary variable (ignoring baseline Time 1).

In diet group 2, there is one outlier (RATSL8S ~ 600). We remove this observation.

RATSL8S1 <- RATSL8S %>%

Finally, we apply a t-test to assess any difference between the treatment groups, and also calculate a confidence interval for this difference.

# Perform a two-sample t-test and observe the differences as seen in in the boxplots of the previous exercise

# Between group 1 and 2
RATSL8S1_12 <- RATSL8S1%>%
  filter(Group == "1"  | Group == "2" )

t.test(mean ~ Group, data = RATSL8S1_12, var.equal = TRUE)

Fit a linear model that conditions on the baseline value.

# Add the baseline from the original data as a new variable to the summary data

Remember: The summary measure approach provides a useful first step in making inferences about the data, but a more complete and a more appropriate analysis will involve fitting a suitable model to the data and estimating parameters that link the explanatory variables of interest to the repeated measures of the response variable.

Analysing the BPRS data set

40 male subjects were randomly assigned to one of two treatment groups and each subject was rated on the brief psychiatric rating scale (BPRS) measured before treatment began (week 0) and then at weekly intervals for eight weeks. The BPRS assesses the level of 18 symptom constructs such as hostility, suspiciousness, hallucinations and grandiosity; each of these is rated from one (not present) to seven (extremely severe). https://mooc.helsinki.fi/pluginfile.php/78192/course/section/3817/MABS4IODS.pdf

The previous model assumes independence of the repeated measures of bprs, and this assumption is highly unlikely. So, now we will move on to consider both some more appropriate graphics and appropriate models.

We will first fit the random intercept model for the same two explanatory variables: week and treatment. Fitting a random intercept model allows the linear regression fit for each subject to differ in intercept from other subjects.

# access library lme4
library(lme4)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## 
## Attaching package: 'Matrix'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     expand, pack, unpack
# Fit the random intercept model with the rat ID as the random effect
BPRS_ref <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (1 | subject), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

# Print the summary of the model
summary(BPRS_ref)

The variability (standard deviation) of subject is quite small, indicating small variation in the intercepts of the regression fits of the individual bprs profiles.

The estimated regression parameters are very similar to those from the previous model. However, the estimated standard error of week is smaller. The reason for the smaller standard errors with the independence model is that the effective sample size for estimating these effects is less than the actual sample size because of the correlated nature of the data, and so the estimates for the independence model are unrealistically precise.

Now we can move on to fit the random intercept and random slope model to the bprs data. Fitting a random intercept and random slope model allows the linear regression fits for each individual to differ in intercept but also in slope. This way it is possible to account for the individual differences in the bprs profiles, but also the effect of time.

# Fit the random intercept and slope model with week and subject as the random effects
BPRS_ref1 <- lmer(bprs ~ week + treatment + (week | subject), data = BPRSL, REML = FALSE)

# print a summary of the model
